**Input:**

```shell
c++ --std=c++17 CreateIndex.cpp $(pkg-config --cflags --libs libmongocxx) -o ./app.out
./app.out
```

**Output:**

```
New index name: default
```

> **Tip:**&#x20;
>
> MacOS Error
>
> MacOS users might see the following error after running the preceding
> commands:
>
> ```sh
> dyld[54430]: Library not loaded: @rpath/libmongocxx._noabi.dylib
> ```
>
> To resolve this error, use the `-Wl,-rpath` linker option to set
> the `@rpath`, as shown in the following code:
>
> ```sh
> c++ --std=c++17 CreateIndex.cpp -Wl,-rpath,/usr/local/lib/ $(pkg-config --cflags --libs libmongocxx) -o ./app.out
> ./app.out
> ```

The MongoDB Search `boolean` type takes the following parameter:

| Option | Type   | Necessity | Description                                                                  |
| ------ | ------ | --------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| type   | string | required  | Human-readable label that identifies this field type. Value must be boolean. |

The following index definition examples use collections in the
[sample data sets](available-sample-datasets). After you
[Load Sample Data Into Atlas](load-sample-data), you can use
these examples to index fields as the dateFacet type.

To learn how to set up and run the following example code, see
Define the Index for the token Type.

The following example creates a MongoDB Search index on the `sample_analytics.customers`
collection and indexes the `active` field as the `boolean` type:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

#include <bsoncxx/builder/basic/document.hpp>
#include <bsoncxx/json.hpp>
#include <mongocxx/client.hpp>
#include <mongocxx/instance.hpp>
#include <mongocxx/uri.hpp>

using bsoncxx::builder::basic::kvp;
using bsoncxx::builder::basic::make_document;

int main(){

    mongocxx::instance instance;
    mongocxx::uri uri("<connection-string>");
    mongocxx::client client(uri);

    auto db = client["sample_analytics"];
    auto collection = db["customers"];

    // instantiate a ``mongocxx::search_index_view`` on your collection
    auto siv = collection.search_indexes();

    {
        auto name = "default";
        auto definition = make_document(
            kvp("mappings", make_document(
                kvp("dynamic", false),
                kvp("fields", make_document(
                    kvp("active", make_document(
                        kvp("type", "boolean")
                    ))
                ))
            ))
        );

        auto model = mongocxx::search_index_model(name, definition.view());

        // Create the search index
        auto result = siv.create_one(model);
        std::cout << "New index name: " << result << std::endl;
    }
}

```

You can use the MongoDB Search `boolean` type to index `true` and `false`
values. You can query fields of type `boolean` using the [equals](equals-ref) and [in](in-ref) operators. You can also [sorting](sort-ref) by indexed `boolean` fields.

You can also use the `boolean` type to index:

- Fields whose value is an array of booleans. To learn more, see
  [How to Index the Elements of an Array](fts-array-ref).

- Boolean fields inside an array of documents indexed as the
  [embeddedDocuments](bson-data-types-embedded-documents) type.

If you enable [dynamic mappings](static-dynamic-mappings), MongoDB Search
automatically indexes fields of type dateFacet. You can
use the **Visual Editor** or the  **JSON Editor** in the Atlas UI to
index fields as the dateFacet type.

